<InfoLayout
  title="About us — Flipkart Assist"
  eyebrow="About us"
  heading="A shopping assistant that talks like a person and thinks like three."
  intro="Flipkart Assist is a demo of what product search feels like when you can just ask — no filters to fiddle with, no twenty open tabs."
>
  <h2>What it is</h2>
  <p>
    Under the hood, every message you send is routed by a supervisor to one of three
    specialist agents: a <strong>Sales agent</strong> for pricing, EMI, and offers, a
    <strong>Technical agent</strong> for specs and side-by-side comparisons, and a
    <strong>Booking agent</strong> that walks you through a (mock) order. They share one
    conversation, so you never have to repeat yourself.
  </p>
  <p>
    Answers come from a real retrieval pipeline — hybrid dense + keyword search over a
    product catalog of laptops, mobiles, TVs, refrigerators, smart watches, and washing
    machines, reranked so the four most relevant products surface first.
  </p>

  <h2>Why it exists</h2>
  <p>
    This is a portfolio project exploring multi-agent orchestration and
    retrieval-augmented generation: LangGraph for agent routing, FastAPI on the backend,
    AstraDB for vector search, Groq for fast LLM inference, and Astro on the frontend.
    The catalog is a snapshot of public Flipkart listings used for demonstration.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Flipkart Assist is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or connected to
    Flipkart.</strong> Nothing here places real orders or moves real money.
  </p>

  <h2>Try it</h2>
  <p>
    Pick a category on the <a href="/">home page</a> and ask anything you'd ask a
    knowledgeable friend — "best phone camera under 30k", "compare these two", "book the
    second one".
  </p>
</InfoLayout>
